{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 15:44:03.513508", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos (EBGP) lab\n----------------------------------------------------------------\n\nSummary\n- Symptom: pc_0_0 cannot reach pc_0_1 (ping 10.0.1.2 from pc_0_0 results in 100% loss; ICMP response is \"Destination Host Unreachable\" sourced from 172.16.0.7).\n- Conclusion: The failure is located at the access/host side for pc_0_1. Control-plane (BGP) and inter‑router forwarding appear converged and present for both /24 host subnets; the immediate root cause is that pc_0_1’s interface is down/unavailable, so the leaf router for that subnet returns host-unreachable.\n- No remediation steps are included (per instructions); findings and evidence only.\n\nKey evidence and observations\n1) Host interface state — pc_0_1\n- pc_0_1 ifconfig / ip addr:\n  - eth0 is in state DOWN (ifconfig shows flags without UP; ip addr output shows eth0 state DOWN).\n  - There is an IP configured: 10.0.1.2/24, but the interface is administratively/down or link down; routing table on pc_0_1 is empty.\n- Effect: pc_0_1 cannot receive L2 frames or respond — host is effectively unreachable at the access layer.\n\n2) Access/leaf interface statistics — leaf_router_0_1\n- leaf_router_0_1 ifconfig:\n  - eth2 = 10.0.1.1/24 and state UP, but RX/TX packet counters on eth2 = 0 (no traffic seen on that interface).\n- Interpretation: leaf sees no L2 traffic toward the host IP on its access interface, consistent with the host NIC/link being down.\n\n3) Ping test (end-to-end behavior)\n- From pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: ping output\n  - All packets fail with \"From 172.16.0.7 icmp_seq=X Destination Host Unreachable\".\n  - Source 172.16.0.7 corresponds to leaf_router_0_1, indicating the packet reached that leaf but the leaf could not deliver at L2 to the host and returned the ICMP unreachable.\n- This confirms the failure is at leaf_router_0_1 -> host adjacency, not earlier in the spine/super-spine fabric.\n\n4) Routing/BGP state across routers\n- BGP tables show the two host subnets (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are being advertised and are present in routing tables on super-spine, spines and leaves:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) and leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201) each show their local /24 as locally originated (0.0.0.0 next-hop / i origin).\n  - spine and super-spine routing tables contain next-hops toward the correct leaf routers for each host subnet.\n- Examples (high‑level):\n  - spine_router_0_0: 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.5, 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7\n  - super_spine_router_0: shows both /24s reachable via the spines\n- No signs of BGP session flaps or missing network advertisements in the captured summaries — BGP convergence appears normal and routes propagate.\n\nLocalization of fault\n- Faulty device / component: pc_0_1 (host) — its eth0 interface is down/unavailable.\n- Affected adjacency: leaf_router_0_1 <-> pc_0_1 link (leaf eth2 shows no traffic; leaf returns host-unreachable).\n- Scope: impact limited to 10.0.1.0/24 (pc_0_1); network-level routing for that subnet is present on routers, so other parts of the fabric are functioning.\n\nRoot cause determination\n- Root cause (most likely): host access interface down (administrative or link down) on pc_0_1. Evidence:\n  - pc_0_1 eth0 state = DOWN; no routing table entries on pc_0_1.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 eth2 up but zero RX/TX, meaning no L2 frames reach the leaf from the host.\n  - Ping triggered an ICMP Destination Host Unreachable from the leaf, showing the leaf could not resolve/deliver to the host’s MAC/ARP.\n- Alternative/secondary causes considered (less likely given captured data):\n  - Physical disconnect or cable issue between pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 (would produce same symptom).\n  - Host firewall or misconfiguration blocking ICMP would cause different behavior — but the host interface is DOWN, so firewall is not the primary cause.\n\nAdditional observations (informational)\n- BGP path diversity is present (spines show multiple paths), and each leaf’s /24 is visible in the global BGP view; no BGP anomalies were observed in the snapshots collected.\n- leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 have appropriate BGP-learned routes pointing to each other via the spine(s); forwarding between pods appears functional from the router perspective.\n- pc_0_0 has a default gateway set to 10.0.0.1; pc_0_0 successfully sent the ping, which traversed the fabric to the destination leaf (as evidenced by the ICMP unreachable returned by that leaf).\n\nSummary statement\n- The network fabric (EBGP and inter‑router forwarding) is converged and operating; the outage is localized to the pc_0_1 access/end-host interface (eth0 DOWN or physical link down). The leaf router for 10.0.1.0/24 is reachable and advertising the subnet, but it cannot forward to the host because the host interface/link is not available.\n\nIf you want, I can run additional checks to further confirm (examples: show ARP table on leaf_router_0_1, re-check link state changes, or attempt to bring pc_0_1 interface up) — but I will not perform remediation unless you request it.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11590, "output_tokens": 2536, "total_tokens": 14126, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 10880}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1216}}}
